post_text: TEAM MUSTANG, It is our hope that you and your family are safe during this time. After the assessment of the district properties, we have evaluated that all WOCCISD facilities have received wind or water damage. We have started recovery and repairs and will keep the community informed of our progress. Once power is restored to our community and families are settled WOCCISD will notify you of the next steps. Our plan is to begin virtual learning during repairs and phase into our in-person instruction as buildings are completed. Please continue to pray for all the communities affected by Hurricane Laura. Stay strong and stay safe MUSTANGS!

Students in grades 9-12 interested in being a part of either the Mustang News Team or the Big Blue Productions Team (video board team), please fill out the application in the link below. Both teams work closely together on projects and have the opportunity to work with all types of video production.

WOCCISD Summer Workouts Shut Down until July 13

West Orange-Cove CISD will shut down summer workouts until July 13. We will reassess the situation at that time.

Coach Thompson, Director of Athletics, WOCCISD, stated, ‚ÄúAfter further consideration, we have decided that it is in the best interest of the students and staff to pause all summer activities for all Mustang athletes due to the recent rise in cases.‚Äù

WOCCISD has not had any new cases since the last announcement on June 27.

We ask that you please keep students at home and adhere to CDC guidelines to help stop the spread of COVID-19. For a list of possible symptoms, please refer to the CDC website at https://www.cdc.gov/.

Stay safe, Mustangs.

post_text: "Exciting things are coming to West Orange-Stark High School engineering program. With the partnership of DOW industries, a $5,000 grant has been awarded to our engineering program, and teachers are being trained in Project Lead the Way curriculum, which promotes STEM education using a hands-on approach to real-world problem-solving experiences. DOW's partnership is also outlining a mentoring program for future Mustang engineers. We are looking forward to a great year to be a Mustang!"

post_text:
Mustang Football Workouts Face Another Positive Case

Friday evening, a parent notified West Orange-Stark coaches that an athlete who attended football workouts this past week has tested positive for COVID-19. Upon further investigation, the local health department has directed a specific group of students and coaches that must quarantine due to close contact with the positive student. The local health department is contacting all participants with further instructions.

Mustang workouts will continue summer programs following protocols put in place. Precautionary health screenings, including daily temperature checks, will continue for all participates in sanctioned activities. Students exhibiting any symptoms of COVID-19 should not participate in district activities. Please follow CDC guidelines if you are exhibiting any symptoms of COVID-19. For a list of possible symptoms, please refer to the CDC website at https://www.cdc.gov/.

Safety is our #1 concern at this time. Stay safe, Mustangs.

https://www.woccisd.net/apps/news/article/1251169

GRADUATION INFORMATION:
Greetings Mustang Family,
COVID-19 has affected our daily interactions, including the celebration of our 2020 graduates. Even though the celebration may have changed, the accomplishments are no less important. Graduation guidelines were set based on TEA requirements for social distancing. Please read the instructions below carefully. Any changes concerning these instructions will be announced on social media, district websites, and at the time of the ceremony.

Graduation Ceremony will be held on Friday, June 5, 2020, at 6:00 p.m. located in the Dan R. Hooks Stadium and Leroy D. Breedlove Field.

This information is also posted on the WOCCISD website at https://www.woccisd.net/apps/news/article/1232902

March 26 at 7:58 PM ¬∑

A Declaration of Disaster and accompanying Emergency Orders have been signed by Mayor Larry Spears Jr. which will become effective at 11:59 pm, March 26, 2020.

The City of Orange feels fortunate that there are minimal positive cases of COVID-19 in Southeast Texas, but believes this declaration and emergency orders will assist in the area-wide effort to limit the public‚Äôs exposure to COVID-19. Citizens are encouraged to read the entirety of the Declaration of Disaster and Emergency Orders.

Additional information concerning the Declaration of Disaster and accompanying Emergency Orders may be found at the following link: http://www.orangetexas.net/declaration-of-disaster-covid-19-3-26-2020/.

City officials and Emergency Management are continuing to monitor the situation and will post updates when available.

post_text:
From Coach Trahan: Thursday, March 5th, WOS girls powerlifting had 3 girls compete at the Regional Meet in Bay City.

Aris Batts finished in 3rd place in the 181lb weight class, where she had a squat of 285lbs, bench press of 105lbs, and a deadlift of 300lbs to finish with a total of 690lbs.

Dasasha Janice also did well as she finished in 4th place in the 114lb weight class, where she had a squat of 195lbs, bench press of 75lbs, and a deadlift of 205lbs to finish with a total of 475lbs.

Nortazia McGhee finished in 4th place in the 259+lb weight class, where she had a squat of 245lbs, bench press of 110lbs, and a deadlift of 310lbs to finish with a total of 665lbs.

Congratulations!

Aris Batts finished in 3rd place in the 181lb weight class, where she had a squat of 285lbs, bench press of 105lbs, and a deadlift of 300lbs to finish with a total of 690lbs.

Nortazia McGhee finished in 4th place in the 259+lb weight class, where she had a squat of 245lbs, bench press of 110lbs, and a deadlift of 310lbs to finish with a total of 665lbs.

Congratulations!

West Orange-Cove CISD, is monitoring the coronavirus (2019-nCov) situation carefully and is implementing proactive measures to ensure the health and safety of students and employees in accordance with the guidance provided by the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC).

According to the CDC, this virus is NOT currently spreading in the United States. Nonetheless, Spring Break season is near and many students, faculty, and staff are expected to travel during that time.

It is best to practice healthy habits including frequent hand washing, covering your mouth and nose when coughing or sneezing, and avoiding contact with sick people.

post_text:
Congratulations to WOSMS Student of the Month for February! Elton Hajdari is a 6th-grade student who excels in almost everything he does. He is willing to go the extra mile to help out. He makes good grades and has amazing classroom behavior. He is a member of the TAME team (Texas Alliance for Minorities in Engineering). During the Regional competition, Elton received the judges' choice for his Engineer Design Challenge. He also placed 4th in the Science portion and placed 3rd in Math. Elton also received the 6th ACE award, which is only awarded to one student from each grade level(academic excellence award). Elton will be advancing to the State Competition in April.

He is pictured with our middle school Principal, Mr. McGrew, and Superintendent Dr. Harris.

Congratulations Mustang Academy Student of the Month!
Megan Dorantes entered the Mustang Academy in September of 2019 after dropping out of high school in the spring of 2019. She desired a smaller environment where she could focus on her studies and gain her diploma at her own pace. She completed all coursework in January 2020, including passing the U. S. History STAAR EOC in December of 2019. Megan is the very first of the Mustang Academy graduates. She is pictured with AAC Coordinator, Christina Anderson, and Superintendent, Dr. Rickie Harris.
text:
Congratulations Mustang Academy Student of the Month!
Megan Dorantes entered the Mustang Academy in September of 2019 after dropping out of high school in the spring of 2019. She desired a smaller environment where she could focus on her studies and gain her diploma at her own pace. She completed all coursework in January 2020, including passing the U. S. History STAAR EOC in December of 2019. Megan is the very first of the Mustang Academy graduates. She is pictured with AAC Coordinator, Christina Anderson, and Superintendent, Dr. Rickie Harris.

post_text:
Congratulations to Ms. Shont'e Arvie, Academic Alternative Center Employee of the Month for February. She is an instructional aide at the alternative campus. She plays an instrumental part in our implementation of the Why Try program, a program used to teach at-risk students better ways to deal with life situations and how to build positive character traits. She makes connections with the students by sharing her experiences to help them change their future for the better. She is a mother, grandmother, and our campus chef.
She is pictured with AAC Coordinator, Christina Anderson, and Superintendent, Dr. Rickie Harris

WOSHS Choir students competed in UIL Solo and Ensemble Contest on February 1st at Little Cypress Mauriceville High School. A total of 18 students earned a superior rating on their solo, and now are eligible for the state competition.. The Texas State Solo and Ensemble Contest (TSSEC) will be held in Austin, Texas in May. This is the first time in years that this many students have qualified for the state competition. Caleb Henson is the Choir Director.

Students are: Back Row L to R: Mr. Henson, Kameron Queen, Raniyah Richardson, Destiny Knox, Wyndie Williams, and Nazingah Watson

Front Row L to R: Brittany Robles, Destiny Miles, Natasha Negron, Nikerria Smith, Jermiyah Amerson, Hannah Chatman and Mycah Brown

Not pictured: Jasmine Smith, Jay'Den Miller, Alexia Hernandez Crochett, Emily Johnson

Thank you and have a great day!

post_text:
It is that time of year!

It is time for WOS Filly tryouts. Eighth- grade students can pick up tryout packets in the front office. Students in ninth through twelfth grade can get packets in their front office.

All packets are due by 4:00 PM on or before February 5th.

Congratulations to the WOCCISD Student of the Month for January, Remy Theriot! Remy is sweet, smart and confident. She is always smiling and ready to learn. She enjoys dance and softball. Remy loves helping others and is an outstanding Mustang!

She is pictured with NELC Principal Vickie Oceguera and Superintendent Dr. Rickie Harris.
